Below is a ~1000-word, well-structured, deeply detailed documentation describing the internal workflow, user experience, and system logic of EarnBuddy based on all the information you’ve shared across conversations.

EarnBuddy — Platform Workflow & Functional Documentation (1000 Words)
EarnBuddy is a collaboration-first ecosystem designed to unify startup roles, freelance projects, community interaction, and event collaboration into a single structured workflow. The core philosophy is simple: opportunities bring people together, community creates energy, and collaboration makes execution possible. EarnBuddy operationalizes this through four main pillars: Startups, Freelancing, Communities (Circles), and Events, supported by a personalized Home Dashboard.

1. Circles: The Collaboration Engine
Circles form the backbone of EarnBuddy. Every interaction—whether joining a team, participating in an event, or engaging with a community—happens inside a Circle. There are three types:

1.1 Opportunity Circles (Private, System-Generated)
These circles are created automatically whenever a user or startup posts an opportunity—either a startup role or a freelancing/colancing project.

Workflow
Opportunity Posted

A Startup founder posts a role (e.g., “Frontend Engineer Intern”).

A Freelancer posts a project requiring contributors under Colancing.

Circle Auto-Creation

The system generates a private Opportunity Circle tied uniquely to the posting.

Application Management

Interested users apply.

The opportunity owner sees all applicants with profile insights (skills, past work, badges, experience).

They can accept, reject, or shortlist candidates.

Actions trigger notifications to applicants.

Circle Membership

All accepted contributors are automatically added to the Opportunity Circle.

Rejected candidates receive status updates (but not access to the circle).

The opportunity owner becomes the “Circle Lead.”

Inside the Opportunity Circle

Task Board (kanban-style or chat-based task assignments).

Real-time chat & file sharing.

Assigned roles and sub-tasks.

Activity logs & progress indicators.

Milestones defined by the startup/project owner.

Opportunity Circles persist for as long as the role/project remains active.

1.2 Community Circles (Public, User-Facing)
Community Circles are public chatrooms built around themes, interests, industries, or regions—e.g., AI Circle, Indie Hackers, Web3 India, Startup Builders, Design Pod, etc.

Role in the Platform
Serve as hubs for PR, networking, discussion, and discoverability.

System recommends Circles based on user interests, skills, and past activity.

Leaders (circle admins) can pin resources, create mini-initiatives, and organize sessions.

Event Creation Ability
Community Circles can create events, but only through collaboration:

Circle A sends a Collab Request to Circle B.

The request includes:

Event concept

Roles needed (speaker, moderator, volunteers)

Target audience

Circle B accepts → Event is created.

This mechanism reinforces EarnBuddy’s core idea: collaboration drives creation.

1.3 Event Circles (Temporary, Auto-Managed)
Event Circles are generated automatically when two community circles collaborate to create an event.

Characteristics
Include members of both community circles.

Have a predefined tenure (from event creation → event completion).

Dissolve or archive after event completion.

Used for:

coordination of event logistics,

sharing event materials (presentations, schedules, posters),

real-time announcements,

volunteer onboarding.

Event Circles unify communities for short-term collaboration.

2. Events Section
The Events page is the “explore board” for everything happening across EarnBuddy communities.

Key Features
Upcoming Events: Workshops, hackathons, pitch nights, founder AMA sessions.

Events by Circles: Filter by communities you belong to.

Your Registered Events: badges, deadlines, and event reminders.

Collaborated Events: Multi-circle events show joint hosting communities.

Each event entry shows:

Date & time

Hosting Circles

Expected audience

Participation type (open, invite-only, mentorship required, etc.)

Event Circle link (once registered)

3. Startups Section
This section is dedicated to founders posting roles or finding collaborators for their ventures.

3.1 Posting Startup Roles
Founders can post:

Full-time roles

Internship roles

Co-founder searches

Equity-based collaboration opportunities

What Happens in System
The moment the role is posted, an Opportunity Circle is created.

Applicants join the opportunity pool.

The founder manages applicants via:

skill match score,

portfolio,

interview scheduling.

Accepted users are added to the circle where work begins.

Differentiator from Freelancing
Startup roles may involve long-term collaboration, equity, or ongoing responsibilities.

Team behaviour resembles building a company.

4. Freelancing (Colancing and Teamlancing)
Freelancing projects follow the same pipeline as Startup opportunities but differ in execution philosophy.

Differences from Startups
Aspect	Freelancing	Startups
Duration	Short-term gigs	Long-term roles
Payment	Fixed/Hourly	Salary/Equity/Co-founder
Execution Style	Colancing (shared workload)	Team leadership & high commitment
Circle Focus	Task fulfillment	Company building
Colancing / Teamlancing
Instead of hiring one freelancer, the project owner can onboard multiple specialized contributors into a single Opportunity Circle.
Examples:

A branding project → logo designer + copywriter + motion graphics artist.

A SaaS landing page → frontend dev + illustrator + UX writer.

EarnBuddy standardizes team-based freelancing.

5. Home Dashboard (Central Activity Hub)
The Home Dashboard provides a personalized overview of everything happening across the user’s EarnBuddy universe.

Components (Detailed)
5.1 Application Statuses
Shows:

Opportunities applied to

Status: pending / accepted / rejected

Interview notifications

Next steps for accepted users

5.2 Circle Activity Feed
Aggregates updates from all circles:

New tasks assigned

Messages @mentioned you

Milestone progress

Event updates

5.3 Recommended Opportunities
Based on:

Skills

Past applications

Circle memberships

Behavior patterns (e.g., active in Web3 talk → show Web3 gigs)

5.4 Recommended Circles
Smart suggestions like:

“People like you are joining Creator’s Lab”

“AI Circle posted a new event”

5.5 Personal Progress Analytics
Number of circles you are part of

Completed tasks

Event participation stats

Contribution badges

5.6 Quick Actions
Buttons for:

Create a Circle

Post an Opportunity

View My Events

Jump into active circles

This dashboard becomes the user’s command center.

6. Notifications System
The platform provides structured, categorized notifications:

Application updates

Circle invitations

Circle activity pings

Event reminders

Collaboration requests

Task assignments

Notifications are grouped by type for clarity.

7. User Profiles
Each profile includes:

Skills and endorsements

Previous circle participation

Contributions in Opportunity Circles

Portfolio

Availability status

Reputation badges (“Top Contributor”, “Circle Hero”, “Freelance Pro”)

Profiles help opportunity owners pick the right team quickly.

8. How All Systems Work Together (E2E Flow)
User joins EarnBuddy → explores Circles.

Applies to a startup role or freelance gig.

If accepted, joins an Opportunity Circle.

Parallelly engages in Community Circles for PR and networking.

Community Circles collaborate → create Events.

User participates in events, gains reputation, and attracts more opportunities.

EarnBuddy becomes a collaboration flywheel where each action increases the probability of growth for users, teams, and communities.

Final Summary
EarnBuddy combines:

Opportunity discovery,

Community-driven events,

Team-based execution, and

Transparent collaboration management

into one cohesive ecosystem powered by Circles.
This document outlines the platform’s complete functional architecture for product development, user onboarding, investor communication, and UX planning.






1. FULL SYSTEM INTERACTION FLOWCHART
Below is a readable, text-based flowchart showing how every module interacts.
After that, I provide a Mermaid flowchart you can paste into Notion, GitHub, Obsidian, Lovable, etc.

1.1 TEXT FLOWCHART (HUMAN-READABLE, SYSTEM-WIDE)
A. User Journey → Dashboard
User Registers/Login
         ↓
System Fetches:
  - User Profile
  - Applications (startup, freelance)
  - Circle Memberships
  - Events Registered
  - Recommendations
         ↓
Home Dashboard Displays:
  - Active Opportunity Circles
  - Community Circles
  - Event Circles
  - Application Statuses
  - Recommended Opportunities
  - Recommended Community Circles
  - Notifications
B. Posting an Opportunity (Startup or Freelance)
User → Post Opportunity Form
         ↓
System Creates Opportunity Record
         ↓
System Auto-Generates:
  - Opportunity Circle (private)
  - Circle Lead = Opportunity Owner
         ↓
Opportunity Appears in Public Listings
C. Applying to an Opportunity
User → Apply
         ↓
System Creates Application Entry
         ↓
Owner Reviews Applications:
   Accept → Add user to Opportunity Circle
   Reject → Notify user
   Shortlist → Status updated
D. Inside an Opportunity Circle
Circle Members Join
         ↓
Circle Contains:
  - Chat
  - Task Board
  - Milestones
  - File Sharing
  - Activity Feed
         ↓
Task Assignments → Push Notifications
E. Community Circles
User Browses → Join Community Circle
         ↓
Chats, Discussions, PR, Networking
         ↓
Circle Leader Can:
  - Pin Resources
  - Start Sub-topics
  - Send Collaboration Requests to Other Circles
F. Creating an Event (via Circle Collaboration)
Circle A → Sends Event Proposal to Circle B
         ↓
Circle B Accepts
         ↓
System Auto-Creates:
  - Event Record
  - Event Circle (temporary)
  - Member List = Members of A + B
         ↓
Event Appears in Global Events Listing
G. Event Participation
User → Registers for Event
         ↓
System Adds User to:
  - Event Participant List
  - Event Circle (if permission allows)
         ↓
Event Day → Reminders, Announcements
H. Notifications Engine
Triggers:

Task Assigned

Application Status Change

Circle Invite

Event Update

Collaboration Request

1.2 MERMAID FLOWCHART (COPY-PASTE READY)
Paste this anywhere that supports Mermaid:

flowchart TD

A[User Login/Register] --> B[Load Dashboard]

B --> C[Fetch Profile, Circles, Applications, Events, Recos]
C --> D[Display Dashboard]

%% Posting Opportunity
D --> E[Post Startup/Freelance Opportunity]
E --> F[Create Opportunity Record]
F --> G[Auto Create Opportunity Circle]

%% Applying to Opportunity
D --> H[User Applies to Opportunity]
H --> I[Create Application Entry]
I --> J[Owner Reviews Applications]

J --> J1[Accept -> Add to Opportunity Circle]
J --> J2[Reject -> Notify User]
J --> J3[Shortlist -> Update Status]

%% Opportunity Circle
J1 --> K[Opportunity Circle Workspace]
K --> K1[Chat]
K --> K2[Task Board]
K --> K3[File Sharing]
K --> K4[Milestones]

%% Community Circles
D --> L[Browse Community Circles]
L --> M[Join Community Circle]
M --> M1[Chat, Networking, PR]
M --> M2[Send Collab Request to Another Circle]

%% Event Creation
M2 --> N[Other Circle Accepts]
N --> O[Create Event Record]
O --> P[Create Event Circle]
P --> Q[Members = Members of Circle A + B]

%% Events Page
D --> R[Browse Events]
R --> S[Register for Event]
S --> S1[Join Event Participants List]

%% Notification
F --> T[Trigger Notification]
J --> T
M2 --> T
O --> T
K --> T
2. DATABASE SCHEMA FOR EARNBUDDY
EarnBuddy needs a hybrid database:

Relational (PostgreSQL / MySQL) for structured data

NoSQL (MongoDB / Firestore) for real-time chats, circle messages, logs

Below is the optimal schema.

2.1 RELATIONAL DATABASE SCHEMA (PostgreSQL)
TABLE: users
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID (PK)	unique
name	varchar	
email	varchar	unique
password_hash	text	
bio	text	
skills	jsonb	list of skills
profile_pic	varchar	
reputation_score	int	gamification
TABLE: circles
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
circle_type	enum(opportunity, community, event)	
name	varchar	auto for opp/event
description	text	
created_by	UUID FK(users.id)	
event_id	UUID FK(events.id) nullable	
is_temporary	boolean	
TABLE: circle_members
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
circle_id	FK(circles.id)	
user_id	FK(users.id)	
role	enum(member, admin, owner)	
TABLE: opportunities
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
type	enum(startup, freelance)	
posted_by	FK(users.id)	
title	varchar	
description	text	
compensation_type	enum(salary, stipend, equity, paid, unpaid)	
timeline	varchar	
circle_id	FK(circles.id)	auto-linked
TABLE: applications
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
opportunity_id	FK(opportunities.id)	
applicant_id	FK(users.id)	
status	enum(pending, accepted, rejected, shortlisted)	
applied_at	timestamp	
TABLE: events
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
name	varchar	
description	text	
created_by_circle	FK(circles.id)	
start_date	timestamp	
end_date	timestamp	
circle_id	FK(circles.id)	event circle
TABLE: event_participants
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
event_id	FK(events.id)	
user_id	FK(users.id)	
TABLE: tasks
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
circle_id	FK(circles.id)	
assigned_to	FK(users.id)	
title	varchar	
description	text	
status	enum(todo, inprogress, completed)	
due_date	date	
TABLE: collab_requests
Field	Type	Notes
id	UUID	PK
from_circle	FK(circles.id)	
to_circle	FK(circles.id)	
proposal	text	
status	enum(pending, accepted, rejected)	
2.2 NoSQL STRUCTURES (MongoDB / Firestore)
Collection: circle_messages
{
  circle_id: UUID,
  messages: [
     {
       msg_id: UUID,
       sender_id: UUID,
       timestamp: ISO,
       content: text,
       attachments: []
     }
  ]
}
Collection: activity_logs
{
  circle_id: UUID,
  activity: [
      { action: "task_created", by: userId, ts: ISO },
      { action: "member_joined", by: userId, ts: ISO }
  ]
}